# GSAP Motion System

GSAP is the default advanced motion system for this project. Framer Motion remains only where already in use (Expertise.tsx AnimatePresence). Do not mix systems on the same element.

## Setup rules

- Import from `gsap` and `gsap/ScrollTrigger` — always register the plugin once at module level
- Register in a `useEffect` or a shared `lib/gsap.ts` init file, never inline per-component
- Always kill/revert in cleanup: `ctx.revert()` on `gsap.context()`, or `trigger.kill()` on individual ScrollTriggers

```ts
// ✅ correct lifecycle pattern
useEffect(() => {
  const ctx = gsap.context(() => {
    gsap.from(ref.current, { opacity: 0, y: 24, duration: 0.7, ease: "power2.out" });
  }, ref);
  return () => ctx.revert();
}, []);
```

## Sequences → timelines

Use `gsap.timeline()` for any orchestrated sequence of 2+ steps. Never chain `.from()` calls with manual `delay:` offsets.

```ts
// ❌ scattered delays
gsap.from(title, { opacity: 0, delay: 0 });
gsap.from(rule,  { opacity: 0, delay: 0.3 });

// ✅ timeline
const tl = gsap.timeline();
tl.from(title, { opacity: 0, y: 20, duration: 0.6, ease: "power2.out" })
  .from(rule,   { scaleX: 0, duration: 0.4, ease: "power2.out" }, "-=0.2");
```

## Stagger

Use `stagger` instead of per-element delays when animating a list or grid.

```ts
gsap.from(".card", { opacity: 0, y: 32, duration: 0.5, ease: "power2.out", stagger: 0.08 });
```

## ScrollTrigger

Use only where scroll-driven choreography is genuinely justified (e.g. section reveals, pinned sequences). Not every element needs a ScrollTrigger — CSS scroll-driven `.reveal` and `.reveal-clip` already handle simple fade-ups.

```ts
ScrollTrigger.create({
  trigger: sectionRef.current,
  start: "top 80%",
  onEnter: () => tl.play(),
  once: true, // prefer once:true for entrance animations
});
```

- Avoid `scrub` + `pin` on mobile — use `gsap.matchMedia()` to disable or simplify
- Prefer `once: true` for entrance animations; reserve continuous scrub for intentional parallax

## Responsive + reduced-motion

Always use `gsap.matchMedia()` for breakpoint or motion-preference differences:

```ts
const mm = gsap.matchMedia();
mm.add("(prefers-reduced-motion: no-preference)", () => {
  // full animation
});
mm.add("(prefers-reduced-motion: reduce)", () => {
  gsap.set(el, { opacity: 1, y: 0 }); // instant, no animation
});
mm.add("(max-width: 767px)", () => {
  // simplified mobile version — no pin, no scrub
});
return () => mm.revert();
```

## Easing conventions

| Use case | Easing |
|---|---|
| Entrance / reveal | `power2.out` |
| Exit / dismiss | `power2.in` |
| Elastic / playful | `back.out(1.4)` |
| Smooth parallax | `none` (linear) |
| Premium, slow reveal | `expo.out` |

## Per-motion documentation

For every non-trivial GSAP animation, add a brief inline comment:
- trigger (scroll / load / hover / click)
- purpose (what user problem it solves)
- duration + easing
- cleanup strategy

```ts
// Trigger: section enters viewport
// Purpose: prevents layout pop — elements arrive smoothly rather than snapping in
// Duration: 0.6s expo.out — premium, unhurried feel
// Cleanup: ctx.revert() on unmount
```

## What NOT to do

- Do not animate `width`, `height`, `top`, `left`, `margin`, `padding` — causes layout thrash; use `transform` and `opacity` only
- Do not use GSAP for hover states that CSS `transition` already handles cleanly
- Do not leave ScrollTrigger instances without cleanup — they accumulate across HMR cycles
- Do not use `gsap.globalTimeline.pause()` — it freezes everything including UI
